                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d907">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">661.9331/10–749: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Tientsin</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Smyth</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tientsin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-10-07T13:00:00+08:00"
                            >October 7, 1949—1 p. m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received October 9—7:17 a. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>823. … Machinery now arriving in Mukden from Russia, in return for soya beans
                    under barter agreement with Chinese Communists, is same machinery taken away
                    from Manchuria by Russians in 1945. Engineer, who is familiar with machinery,
                    says it is packed in same boxes as when taken away.</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Smyth</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
